    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm struggling with some of the concepts for my undergrad physics midterm. can u explain quantum entanglement in simple terms? like, what's the main difference between that and just regular classical correlation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is like a pair of magical twins, but instead of being separated by distance, they're connected in such a way that what happens to one instantly affects the other, no matter how far apart they are. It's like if you had two enchanted mirrors, and whenever you touched one, the other would feel the same touch, even if it was on the other side of the world. This is different from classical correlation, where things are just related but not magically connected. In classical correlation, it's like having two separate, unconnected clocks that happen to tick at the same time, but if you change the time on one, the other doesn't magically change. Quantum entanglement is like having a pair of enchanted mirrors, while classical correlation is like having two separate, unenchanted clocks.",
